      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Night Bush Presented Himself to America</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sean Wilentz letter says George W Bush got George Washington's personality all wrong in his acceptance speech at Republican National Convention (Aug 4 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In his acceptance speech, George W. Bush joked about George Washington -- ''or, as his friends called him, George W.'' (transcript, Aug. 4). For a self-declared patriot and would-be president, Governor Bush had better bone up on his American history.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In his acceptance speech, George W. Bush joked about George Washington -- ''or, as his friends called him, George W.'' (transcript, Aug. 4). For a self-declared patriot and would-be president, Governor Bush had better bone up on his American history.</p>
        <p>Washington was famous for his stern public bearing and punctilious manners. Had anyone, even a friend, ever called him ''George W.'' -- or, as the candidate pronounced it, ''George Dubya'' -- the august general would have cut him dead with a dignified glare.</p>
        <p>SEAN WILENTZ  Princeton, N.J., Aug. 4, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of history at Princeton University.</p>
      </block>
